HTML- Level 2

        1.  Inline vs Block Elements:
                Block elements-
                        Takes up the full-width available (whole block.)
                        Start from new line.
                        e.g., heading element, paragraph element
                Inline elements-
                        Takes up only necessary width.
                        Don't start from new line.
                        e.g., anchor element, image element

        2.  Div Element:
                Doesn't have any of its own functionality.
                Div is a container used to hold other HTML elements or group elements together.
                It is a block element.
                Syntax: <div>HTML_content</div>

        3.  Span element:
                Generic container used to hold other HTML elements or group together.
                It is an inline element.
                Syntax: <span>html_content</span>

        4.  Hr Tag:
                Page divider, used to horizonatally seperate pages.
                Syntax: </hr>

        5.  Sub and Sup Tag:
                Subscript and Superscript.
                e.g., <p>a<sup>2</sup></p>
                        <p>H<sub>2</sub>O</p>

        6.  Semantic Markup:
                It is the markup that relates to the meaning of content.
                Types of tag:
                        i.  Semantic- eg., <h1>, <p>, <img>
                        ii. non-semantic-   <div>, <span>
                Benefit:
                        i.  Website's layout become structured.
                        ii. Website becomes SEO friendly.
                        iii.Readable + Screen Reader, enhances UX.

        7.  Semantic Tags:
                i.  <header>Text</header>   To display the header of the webpage.
                ii. <main>Text</main>       To display the main content of the webpage.
                iii.<footer>Text</footer>   To display the footer of the webpage.
                iv. <nav>Text</nav>         Used for navigation from current section/webpage to some another section/webpage.
                v.  <article>Text</article> 
                vi. <section>Text</section> Similar to div tag, but helpful for semantic markup and seo.
                vii.<aside>Text</aside>     Used to provide related links.

        8.  HTML Entities:
                An html entitiy is a piece of text ("String") that begins with an ampersand(&) and ends with a semicolon(.).
                Used to display reserved characters (which would otherwise be interpreted as html code), and an invisible characters (like non-breaking spaces.)
                Can also used in place of characters that are difficult to type with a standard keyboard.
                Browser interprets them and renders corrrect character.
                Can be easily searched using Google or using MDN.

        9.  Emmets:
                i.  Parent-Child relationship: constructed using '>' in html.
                        e.g., p>div>b>
                ii. Sibling relationship:  constructed using '+' in html.
                        e.g., p>div+b
                iii.Multiplication: constructed using '*' in html.
                        e.g., ul>li*5
                iv. Boilerplate: '!'

        10. What is HTML5?
                The term HTML5 is essentially a buzzword that refers to a set of modern web technologies.
                This includes the HTML Living Standard, along with Javascript APIs to enhance storage, multimedia, and hardware access.
                HTML5 consists of two things:
                        i.  new features/upgrades in HTML
                        ii. other things/features not part of HTML

        11. How HTML works?
                HTML Standard is a document that tells to the browser how HTML should work.
                HTML code -> browser -> renders webpage (according to the html standard.)

