HTML- Level 3

        1. Tables in HTML:
                Tables are used to represent real life table data.
                
                Main Row of table- header

                Tags to create a table:
                        i.      <caption>Text</caption> Used for giving a title to the table.
                        ii.     <tr>Text</tr>           Used to display table row. (row)
                        iii.    <th>Text</th>           Used to display table header. (header)
                        iv.     <td>Text</td>           Used to display table data. (data)
                        v.      <thead></thead>         Used to wrap table header. (semantics)
                        vi.     <tbody><tbody>          Used to wrap table body. (semamtics)
                        vii.    <tfoot></tfoot>         Used to wrap table footer. (semantics)

                Note: <th> and <td> comes under the <tr> tag.

        2. Colspan and Rowspan Attributes:
                Used to create cells which spans over multiple rows and columns.

                e.g., <th colspan="2">Price</th>
                      <th rowspan="2">Item</th>

        3. Forms in HTML:
                <form>form_content</form>

                Action attribute inside form:   Action attribute is used to define what action
                                                needs to be performed when a form is submitted
                                                or where the form data should be sent.

                Different Form Elements:

                1.      Input:
                                Used to create multiple form controls.
                                There are multiple types of inputs that can be created using type attribute.

                                Attributes:
                                1.      type- indicates type of the input
                                2.      placeholder- indicates default text to show in the input block to user
                                3.      name-   name of the form control. Submitted with the form as part of a name/value pair.
                                                syntax: <input type="text" placeholder="enter name" id="username" name="username"/>

                2.      Label:
                                Label element represents a caption for an item in a user interface.
                                <input> and name of the input should come inside this tag.

                                Label Classical Approach (Which we'll be using)
                                        Using 'for' in <label> and, 'id' in <input>
                                        Syntax: <label for="username">Enter your Username:</label>
                                                <input type="text" id="username">

                3.      Button:
                                Type attribute:
                                i.      Type submit:    <button type="submit">submit</button>
                                ii.     Type button:    <button type="button">do something</button>
                                iii.    Type reset:     <button type="reset">do something</button>

                4.      Checkbox Input Element:  
                                Syntax: 
                                        <label for="age">I am 18+</label>
                                        <input type="checkbox" name="age" id="age" checked/>
                                                here 'checked' represents by defalt checked for checkbox
                                                we can write 'unchecked' also.

                5.      Radio Button Input Element:
                                Syntax:
                                        <label for="apple">Apple</label>
                                        <input type="radio" id="apple" name="fruit" value="apple">

                                        <label for="mango">Mango</label>
                                        <input type="radio" id="mango" name="fruit" value="mango">

                6.      Dropdown:       
                                Syntax:
                                        <select name="profession" id="profession">
                                                <option value="student">Student</option>
                                                <option value="dev">Developer</option>
                                        </select>

                7.      Range Input Element:
                                Syntax:
                                        <label for="volume">Volume</label>
                                        <input id="volume" type="range" min="0" max="100" name="vol"/>

                8.      Text Area Tag:
                                Syntax:
                                        <label for="feedback">Please provide your valuable feedback:</label>
                                        <textarea id="feedback"></textarea>









